- var currentPage = 'Alerts'
doctype html
html(lang='en')
  include ./includes/_head
  body
    include ./includes/_sidebarNav
    .main-content.container-fluid
      h1 Alerts
      p
        | Alerts provide #[strong contextual feedback messages for typical user actions], as well as alerting them to important information they may need to know. Information and warning messages usually appear at the top of a page, under the Success and error messages might appear above a form. Use the appropriate color to match the purpose of your message.

      h3 Guidelines
      ul
        li Keep alerts to 55-75 characters including spaces
        li Use only one alert per page
        li Alerts should have a time limit and be removed promptly

      h3 Example alerts
      h4 Success:
      .alert.alert-success
        span.icon-checkmark-circle2
        strong Well done.
        |  You successfully filled out this form.
      p
        strong When to use:
        |  Success messages such as properly submitting a form

      h4 Warning:
      .alert.alert-warning
        span.icon-warning2
        strong Important!
        |  Choose an in-network primary care provider to help lower your healthcare costs.
      p
        strong When to use:
        |  Warning messages such as letting members know they need a primary care physician before seeing a doctor

      h4 Danger:
      .alert.alert-danger
        span.icon-warning2
        strong Error:
        |  Missing info
      p
        strong When to use:
        |  Error messages such as filling out a form incorrectly; when we won’t let user progress any further without providing the requested info, or when user is being given a chance to make a decision that is irreversible,
        |       hard to change, or has legal implications (for example, granting permissions for claims access).
      h3 More information on error messages
      p
        | When users get an error message, they are probably feeling confused, stressed, frustrated, even angry.

      h4 Tips
      ul
        li Offer a solution or next step.
        li Be straightforward. Explain what's going on right away.
        li Be calm. Don’t use exclamation points or alarming words like “alert” or "immediately."
        li Be serious. Don’t joke around with people who are frustrated.



    include ./includes/_scripts
